Stolen Childhood; Not a Gender Activism problem

Children those between the ages 5-17 years engaged in any economic activity or household chore are counted as child labourer . We try to visualise the rates of children engaged in child labour across the globe

Global Distribution of Child Labour (Total %)

This map shows the distribution of child labour globally. Brighter countries have higher child labour rates. Countries with missing data are shown in grey.

Code 
import polars as pl
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
from plotnine import *

# 1. Loading UNICEF data from my Google Drive
csv_url = "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1vB5XSP-FoSzD56Gnp51fGyLduLE5M5m_/export?format=csv&gid=326492224"
unicef_indicator_1 = pl.read_csv(csv_url)

# 2. Keeping only 'Total' sex
child_labour_total = (
    unicef_indicator_1
    .filter(pl.col("sex") == "Total")
    .group_by("country")
    .agg(pl.col("obs_value").mean().alias("mean_labour"))
)

# 3. Loading World shapefile
world = gpd.read_file("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvkelso/natural-earth-vector/master/geojson/ne_110m_admin_0_countries.geojson")

# 4. Merging UNICEF data with world map
world = world.merge(child_labour_total.to_pandas(), left_on="ADMIN", right_on="country", how="left")

# 5. Exploinge MultiPolygons to Polygons
world = world.explode(index_parts=False)

# 6. Converting geometry to x, y for plotnine manually
world['x'] = world.geometry.apply(lambda geom: geom.exterior.coords.xy[0] if geom and hasattr(geom, 'exterior') else None)
world['y'] = world.geometry.apply(lambda geom: geom.exterior.coords.xy[1] if geom and hasattr(geom, 'exterior') else None)

# 7. Flattening x and y into a DataFrame
rows = []
for idx, row in world.iterrows():
    if row['x'] is not None:
        for xi, yi in zip(row['x'], row['y']):
            rows.append({
                'long': xi,
                'lat': yi,
                'mean_labour': row['mean_labour'],
                'group': row['ADMIN']
            })
world_df = pd.DataFrame(rows)

# 8. Plotting using plotnine
(
    ggplot(world_df)
    + aes(x='long', y='lat', group='group', fill='mean_labour')
    + geom_polygon(color='white')
    + coord_fixed()
    + scale_fill_continuous(name="Child Labour (%)", na_value="grey")
    + theme_void()
    + labs(title="Global Distribution of Child Labour (517 years)")
)

Enhanced Map of Global Distribution (Total %)

This map drawn with Matplotlib rather than Plotnine shows the distribution of child labour globally. Darker countries have higher child labour rates. Like the last map, countries with missing data are shown in grey but do not get distorted by their polygonal shapes.

Code 
import polars as pl
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# 1. Loading UNICEF data from Google Sheets
csv_url = "https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1vB5XSP-FoSzD56Gnp51fGyLduLE5M5m_/export?format=csv&gid=326492224"
unicef_indicator_1 = pl.read_csv(csv_url)

# 2. Keeping only 'Total' sex and calculating the mean labour
child_labour_total = (
    unicef_indicator_1
    .filter(pl.col("sex") == "Total")
    .group_by("country")
    .agg(pl.col("obs_value").mean().alias("mean_labour"))
)

# 3. Loading World shapefile
world = gpd.read_file("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvkelso/natural-earth-vector/master/geojson/ne_110m_admin_0_countries.geojson")

# 4. Merging UNICEF data with world map
world = world.merge(child_labour_total.to_pandas(), left_on="ADMIN", right_on="country", how="left")

# 5. Plotting using geopandas
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(15, 10))
world.plot(column='mean_labour', cmap='OrRd', legend=True, missing_kwds={'color': 'lightgrey', 'label': 'No Data'}, ax=ax)
ax.set_title("Global Distribution of Child Labour (517 years)", fontsize=24)
ax.set_axis_off()
plt.show()

Child Labour by Gender across Countries

This bar chart compares the percentage of boys and girls engaged in child labour across the five different countries. Boys consistently show higher rates than girls, reinforcing gendered labour patterns. Haiti, Tonga and Ethiopia have the highest gap between male and female child workforce. On the other extreme, Colombia and Rwanda have the highest gap between female and male child workforce.

Code 
import polars as pl
from plotnine import *

# Loading UNICEF data again (fresh)
unicef_indicator_1 = pl.read_csv("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1vB5XSP-FoSzD56Gnp51fGyLduLE5M5m_/export?format=csv&gid=326492224")

# Filtering Male and Female
gender_gap = (
    unicef_indicator_1
    .filter(pl.col("sex").is_in(["Male", "Female"]))
    .filter(pl.col("country").is_in(["Haiti", "Tonga", "Ethiopia", "Rwanda", "Colombia"]))
    .group_by(["country", "sex"])
    .agg(pl.col("obs_value").mean().alias("mean_labour"))
)

# Plotting
(
    ggplot(gender_gap.to_pandas())
    + aes(x="country", y="mean_labour", fill="sex")
    + geom_bar(stat="identity", position="dodge")
    + labs(x="Country", y="Child Labour (%)", title="Child Labour by Gender")
    + theme_minimal()
)

Relationship between Male Child Labour and Economic Wealth

This scatterplot shows the relationship between Male Child Labour percentages and economic wealth (GDP per capita as proxy). The trendline suggests that as wealth increases, child labour decreases.

How Wealth chases away Child Labour

This time series plot shows the decline of child labour and the ascent of Capital in UK through historical data across the last century. The data is from the website Our World in Data. We chose UK because its growth was more geographically uniform than the US which saw westward expansion. UK was also isolated from mainland Europe to remain relatively unaffected by geo-political events like foreign occupation or toppling of governments, both monarchial and democratic.

Code 
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Source: OurWorldInData.org - Historical GDP and Child Labour Datasets

# Creating combined historical dataset
data = {
    "year": [1800, 1820, 1840, 1860, 1880, 1900, 1920, 1940, 1960],
    "UK_child_labour_percent": [25, 22, 20, 15, 10, 7, 3, 1, 0],
    "UK_GDP_per_capita": [3200, 3500, 4000, 4500, 5000, 7000, 9000, 12000, 16000],
    "USA_child_labour_percent": [None, None, 23, 20, 18, 14, 10, 5, 1],
    "USA_GDP_per_capita": [None, None, 2500, 3200, 4000, 5500, 7500, 10500, 14000]
}

df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Plotting data for UK
fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))

color = 'tab:blue'
ax1.set_xlabel('Year')
ax1.set_ylabel('UK Child Labour (%)', color=color)
ax1.plot(df['year'], df['UK_child_labour_percent'], color=color, marker='o', label='Child Labour %')
ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color)

# Second y-axis
ax2 = ax1.twinx()
color = 'tab:red'
ax2.set_ylabel('UK GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)', color=color)
ax2.plot(df['year'], df['UK_GDP_per_capita'], color=color, linestyle='--', marker='x', label='GDP per Capita')
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color)

fig.tight_layout()
plt.title('UK: Child Labour % vs GDP per Capita (1800-1960)')
plt.show()
